  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Limited scope and enforcement\n\n2. Major Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Introduced global standards for combating money laundering\n- Expanded regulations across financial institutions\n\n3. Key Legislative Developments\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986, US)\n- EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Stricter customer verification processes\n\n4. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Broader definitions of financial crimes\n- Stronger penalties for non-compliance\n- Technology-enabled monitoring systems\n\n5. Contemporary Focus\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Risk-based approach to compliance\n- Enhanced due diligence\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Targeting terrorist financing\n\n6. Technological Adaptation\n- AI and machine learning for detection\n- Advanced transaction monitoring\n- Real-time risk assessment tools\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, addressing emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
